rust-p2w
========

A Rust reimplementation of the p2w Python-subset -> WebAssembly (WAT) compiler,
built for the AcornSTEM K-12 IDE.

This project derives from two MIT-licensed works:

1. p2w (semantic reference + WAT output conventions)
   The Python subset accepted, the host-import contract
   (env.write_char / write_i32 / write_i64), and the runnable-module shape
   (exported `_start`) are modeled on p2w.

   p2w — Copyright (c) 2024-2026 Stefane Fermigier
   https://git.sr.ht/~sfermigier/p2w
   Licensed under the MIT License (full text below).

2. ruff_python_parser (parser design reference)
   The front-end architecture — tokenizer with INDENT/DEDENT/NEWLINE and
   bracket-depth newline suppression, plus a recursive-descent + Pratt
   expression parser — follows the design of Ruff's Python parser. No source
   is copied verbatim; if any module is later lifted directly, its copyright
   header is preserved here.

   Ruff — Copyright (c) 2022 Charles Marsh
   https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff
   Licensed under the MIT License.

================================================================================
Ideas / inspiration (concepts only — NO code read or used)
================================================================================

The projects below informed *design ideas* in AcornSTEM. No source code from any
of them was read, copied, or adapted — only public descriptions (READMEs,
overviews) were consulted. The implementations here are independent
re-expressions of the underlying (uncopyrightable) concepts. Listed for honest
attribution and to mark the clean-room boundary. License noted where known, but
nothing here depends on those licenses since no code is used.

1. Binarian (farkon00) — https://github.com/farkon00/binarian — MIT
   - The explicit `drop` keyword (visible, programmer-directed memory lifetime)
     informed our idea of leaning into Python's own `del` as a teachable
     last-use / reuse hint that the compiler can act on (drop-reuse / rc==1 fast
     path) and the IDE can visualize. See MEMORY_MANAGEMENT.md.
   - The AST-visualization tooling pattern (an opt-in graph render of the parsed
     program) informed the idea of an AST view with a lifetime/reuse overlay.

